The fix is clean and complete. Let me also verify that `setMaxAttempts` is not unused (Biome strict mode will warn about unused variables). Since no API currently returns `maxAttempts`, `setMaxAttempts` is technically unused at runtime, but it is needed for future population. Let me check if Biome would flag it.

The `setMaxAttempts` setter is part of the destructured `useState` return and is used in the declaration itself — Biome typically does not flag unused state setters. The variable `maxAttempts` is used at lines 2071 and 2073, so it is definitely used. The setter being unused is standard practice when you plan to populate it later, and Biome does not flag state setter functions as "unused variables."

Here is a summary of the changes made:

**File changed:** `/Users/thamsanqamoyo/Documents/code/jem-open/jem-sec-attest/app/[tenant]/training/page.tsx`

**Change 1 — added state variable (line 552):**
```ts
const [maxAttempts, setMaxAttempts] = useState<number>(3);
```
Added alongside the other `useState` declarations in the `TrainingPage` component. Initialized to `3`, which matches the server-side default (`tenant.settings.training?.maxAttempts ?? 3`).

**Change 2 — replaced hardcoded `3` in `renderFailedReview` (lines 2071 and 2073):**
```tsx
// Before
aria-label={STRINGS.attemptCounter(attemptNumber, 3)}
{STRINGS.attemptCounter(attemptNumber, 3)}

// After
aria-label={STRINGS.attemptCounter(attemptNumber, maxAttempts)}
{STRINGS.attemptCounter(attemptNumber, maxAttempts)}
```

**Why no API population yet:** Neither the session GET route (`/api/training/[tenant]/session`) nor the evaluate POST route (`/api/training/[tenant]/evaluate`) returns `maxAttempts` in their responses. The state variable is wired up and ready — when those routes are extended to return `maxAttempts`, a single `setMaxAttempts(data.maxAttempts)` call in the appropriate fetch handler will propagate the tenant-configured value throughout the UI.

